revision.text:
[[Image:Carom Billiards EC Brandenburg Havel-GER 2013-04-20 18-Serdar Gümüs (Billiard Artistique-Final).JPG|thumb|Artistic billiards final at the 2013 European Carom Billiards Championship.]] '''Artistic billiards''', sometimes called '''fantasy billiards''' or '''fantaisie classique''', is a [[carom billiards]] discipline in which players compete at performing 76 preset shots of varying difficulty. Each set shot has a maximum point value assigned for perfect execution, ranging from a four-point maximum for lowest level difficulty shots, and climbing to an 11-point maximum for shots deemed highest in difficulty level. There are a total of 500 points available to a player, representing the combined value of a perfect score on all 76 shots, although not all games are played with the full shot catalogue. The governing body of the sport is the [[Confédération International de Billard Artistique]] (CIBA).
Each shot in an artistic billiards match is played from a well-defined position (in some venues within a two millimetre tolerance), and each shot must unfold in an established manner. Players are allowed three attempts at each shot. In general, the shots making up the game &ndash; even four-point shots &ndash; require a high degree of skill, devoted practice and specialized knowledge to perform. Such shots often require extremes in [[Billiard techniques|shot-making techniques]] that are not often employed in other games, such as {{Cuegloss|Force follow|force follows}}, {{Cuegloss|Draw|force draws}}, precision multiple-rail {{Cuegloss|Kick shot|kicking}}, {{Cuegloss|Jump shot|jumps}} and {{Cuegloss|Massé|massés}} combined with outlandish use of {{Cuegloss|English|english}} ({{Cuegloss|Sidespin|sidespin}}).
[[Image:Billard Artistique Figur A10.png|220px|thumb|A {{Cuegloss|Massé|massé}} shot around a pin; this is Figure A10, worth 10 points.]] Players may use up to twenty separate [[cue stick|cues]] providing different performance functions.{{Fact|date=February 2010}} For example, performing massés may require a cue with a very large diameter terminus and a specialized {{Cuegloss|Cue tip|cue tip}}, while jumping may require a short, {{Cuegloss|Jump cue|light cue}} with a flat (rather than rounded), very hard and also wider cue tip than a playing cue. Some shots may require the use of props such as a small {{Cuegloss|Pin|pin}} placed precisely on the {{Cuegloss|Slate|table surface}} and around which the player is required to make the {{Cuegloss|Cue ball|cue ball}} pass on a designated side ''(see Figure A10 illustration)''. For the most part, top artistic billiard players specialize in the game to the exclusion of all others.{{Fact|date=February 2010}}
World title competition first started in 1986 and required the use of [[ivory]] balls. However, this requirement was dropped in 1990.{{Fact|date=February 2010}} The highest score ever achieved in world competition was 374, by the [[French people|Frenchman]] [[Jean Reverchon]] in 1992, while the highest score in competition overall is 427 set by the [[Belgian people|Belgian]] [[Walter Bax]] in 2006.<ref name="EV">{{cite web |url=http://home.scarlet.be/~ev908555/Tornooien/Uitslagen/Tornooi%204%20f-b%20lugo.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070322110234/http://home.scarlet.be/~ev908555/Tornooien/Uitslagen/Tornooi%204%20f-b%20lugo.htm |dead-url=yes |archive-date=March 22, 2007 |title=Iwan Simonis ranking Artistiek biljarten, BC Lugo 10 - 11 - 12 maart 2006 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |work=VAS - Online |location=[[Ravels, Belgium]] |publisher=Vereniging Artistik Spielers |year=2007 |language=Dutch |accessdate=February 26, 2010 |df= }}</ref> The game is played predominantly in [[Western Europe]], especially in France, Belgium and the [[Netherlands]].{{Fact|date=February 2010}} The game employs a specialized vocabulary, chiefly derived from [[French language|French]] words, encompassing many terms that have no analogues in other [[cue sports]] disciplines. Some examples are ''coup fouetté'' ("whip shot"; a type of force follow); ''massé coulé'' (a massé shot with follow) and ''piqué'' (describes either a massé shot with no english, or a shot in which the cue stick is steeply angled, but not held quite as vertical as it is in full massé).{{Fact|date=February 2010}}
==Artistic pool== {{Main|Trick shot}} '''Artistic pool''' trick shot competitions on [[pocket billiards]] tables, inspired by artistic billiards, began in 1993 in the US at an amateur level and in 2000 professionally and internationally, featuring fifty-six pre-set shots to attempt.<ref name="ArtisticPoolPlayers1">{{Cite web|title=2005 / 2006 Shot Program |url=http://www.artisticpoolplayers.com/shot_program/shot_program_current.php |work=ArtisticPoolPlayers.com |publisher=Artistic Pool and Trick Shot Association |year=2005 |accessdate=2007-07-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630093356/http://www.artisticpoolplayers.com/shot_program/shot_program_current.php |archivedate=30 June 2007 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref><ref name="ArtisticPool.org1">{{Cite web|title='Artistic Pool' History|url=http://www.artisticpool.org/about/|work=ArtisticPool.org|last=Rossman|first=Tom|publisher=Artistic Pool and Trick Shot Association|year=2003|accessdate=2007-07-23| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070713205419/http://www.artisticpool.org/about/| archivedate= 13 July 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>
